This trades off the burden between implementers of StructuredCoders to all callers of verifyDeterministic. It would be better if the StructuredCoder.verifyDeterministic was final and also defined a different method that should be overridden like verifySelfIsDeterministic (but with a much better name).

This could easily be altered to something like `verifyComponentsDeterministic`; these have "replacements" in the static methods `Coder.verifyDeterministic(Coder<?>, String, List<Coder<?>>)`

If the methods are kept, they should certainly be made final. I would like to avoid the suggestion that the verifyDeterministic methods are interchangeable, given that only the argument-free version will be called by the runner.
I'll merge then. Looks like the failure is GCP API surface.

These methods are silly at best, whether they are `protected` methods (yuck!) or static utilities. No actual coder needs this generalization. Every structured coder has some small number of component coders. The loop is less readable, through needless indirection as well as visual complexity, and results in an inadequate error message. Every coder _should_ improve upon the underlying error message that the loop would produce.

And, tellingly, there is no sensible default for a structured coder. Knowing that it is defined by its components tells you nothing about its determinism.
I also want to say that all of my comments are just stylistic and they do not need to be fixed for the API freeze.
I am going to open a cherry-pick of this PR to the release, since I believe it is a good change that is low risk and worthwhile.
(just checking that there is no neglected `ValidatesRunner` test that this affects - the precommit is known to be good)
